Introduction¶

In this project, we will be performing Exploratory Data Analysis on a data set from Prosper, an American marketplace lending platform, with over $9 billion in funded loans.

Our data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. The analysis is structured, going from simple univariate relationships up through multivariate relationships to summarize the characteristics of features that can affect the annual percentage rate and outcome of a loan.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are originally 113,937 loans in the dataset with 81 features on each loan entry. Most variables in the dataset are numeric in nature, with a few ordinal factor variables. However, since I will be focused on loans with a ProsperScore, i.e loans originated after July 2009, the dataset has now been trimmed down to 84,853 loans with 14 variables of interest.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting a loan's annual percentage rate (APR) and outcome status. Key features for my analysis are CreditScoreRange and BorrowerAPR

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

A number of features in the dataset could affect the APR and outcome of a loan to varying degrees, but in addition to my main features of interest, I will also investigate the following 12 features:

  • 'Term' 'LoanStatus' 'ProsperScore' 'ListingCategory' 'EmploymentStatus' 'OpenCreditLines' 'TradesNeverDelinquent' RevolvingCreditBalance 'BankcardUtilization' 'TotalTrades' 'IncomeRange' 'LoanOriginalAmount'.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will investigate distributions of individual variables. I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main feature of interest: CreditScoreRange.

What is the distribution of Credit Score ranges?

In [19]:
# Bar plot of credit score ranges
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
sns.countplot(data=loans, y='CreditScoreRange', color=base_color);

We see that the vast majority of borrowers had a credit score between 660 - 719 with the most frequent range between 660 - 679. There is a slight right skew in the distribution with higher credit scores having less borrowers.

The next main feature of interest is the BorrowerAPR (Annual Percentage Rate) which represents the total cost of a loan to a borrower. Let us see the distribution of BorrowerAPR.

In [20]:
# Plot a histogram to show distribution of Borrower APR
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
bin_size = 0.005
bins = np.arange(loans.BorrowerAPR.min(), loans.BorrowerAPR.max()+bin_size, bin_size)

plt.hist(data=loans, x='BorrowerAPR', bins=bins)
plt.xlabel('Annual Percentage Rate (%)');

I selected a small bin for this plot, and from the distribution, we see a large spike in frequency at the bar around the 0.35-0.36 range, followed by a steep drop. This indicates that most borrowers in our dataset have a high APR of 35%-36%.

OpenCreditLines allows a borrower to access credit repeatedly up to a specific maximum limit. Let us see the distribution of open credit lines.

In [21]:
# Plot a histogram to show distribution of Open credit lines on a normal scale
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
bin_size = 1
bins = np.arange(0, 54+bin_size, bin_size)
plt.hist(data=loans, x='OpenCreditLines', bins=bins)
plt.xlabel('Open Credit Lines')
plt.title('Open Credit Lines on Normal scale');

# Plot credit lines on a square root scale
def sqrt_trans(x, inverse=False):
    if not inverse:
        return np.sqrt(x)
    else:
        return x ** 2

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
bin_size = 0.6
bin_edges = np.arange(0, sqrt_trans(loans.OpenCreditLines.max())+bin_size, bin_size)
plt.hist(loans.OpenCreditLines.apply(sqrt_trans), bins=bin_edges)
tick_locs = np.arange(0, sqrt_trans(loans.OpenCreditLines.max())+1, 1)
plt.xticks(tick_locs, sqrt_trans(tick_locs, inverse=True).astype(int))
plt.title('Open Credit Lines on Square root scale');

OpenCreditLines is an interesting variable for loan prediction and so I subplotted a transformed scale for better insight. On the normal scale, we see a uni-modal and right-skewed distribution with the peak between 8-10. Lesser frequencies are seen in increasing count of open credit lines. On the square root scale however, the distribution does not differ much from the standard scale but appears roughly normal.

The revolving credit balance data has a wide range of values but the distribution is set on the far left of the axes, necessitating further investigation with a transformed scale.

We see very large spikes in frequency at the bars around 4,000, 9,000 and 15,000; frequency gradually trails off until the next spike. Tradelines however, peak at around 20 and slightly skews to the right with very few credit profiles having more than 80 tradelines, and few having delinquent trades.

# Define a function to set jitters
def jitter(ax):
    """ To offset datapoints and create jitters. """
    offsets = ax.get_offsets()
    offsets[:, 0] += np.random.uniform(-0.2, 0.2, offsets.shape[0]) #jitter along the x-axis with a precision of 0.2
    ax.set_offsets(offsets)
In [48]:
# Define a function to assign axes labels and x-axis limits
def plot(plt, xlabel, ylabel):
    """Quick hack for assigning labels """
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    xmin, xmax = plt.xlim() 
    plt.xlim(xmin-0.01, xmax+0.01) # make room for jitters
    plt.xticks(rotation=30)

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Conclusions¶

Our dataset originally contains 81 variables with 113,937 entries, and with so many variables, it was tricky to select the variables to explore without domain knowledge. Using the provided dictionary, google and Prosper, I was properly guided on what each variable meant. I chose Credit score as a main feature of interest on realizing how important the score of a potential borrower is to a lender, and Borrower APR because of how significant it is to potential borrowers. Since the dataset is entries of loans from Prosper, I decided to analyze the entries with a Prosper Score, which also happened to be loans originated after July 2009. Subsetting the dataframe to this criteria trimmed the data down to 84,853 entries with 15 selected features for exploration.

The exploration was structured from simple univariate relationships to multivariate relationships to summarize the characteristics of features that can affect the annual percentage rate (APR) and outcome of a loan. To summarize our exploratory analysis-

  • Most credit profiles had average credit scores between 660-719 and high APRs of 35%-36%.
  • Borrower APR reduced with increasing orders of Prosper score, Credit score and Income range but credit profiles with lengthier loan terms, smaller loan amounts and larger revolving balance incurred higher rates.
  • We could see an increase in number of trades proportional to an increase in the number of open credit lines, and also, a fair number of trades in the dataset were delinquent with about 10% of the loans been either past due, defaulted or charged off. However, with current loans excluded, the proportion of these loans stood at about 30%.
  • Finally, we could see that a lot of the loans in the dataset are currently active and were taken out for debt consolidation. Most of these loans were taken by employed folks with credit scores between 660-719, and majority span for a period of 36months.

    While Credit score, Income range, Prosper score, length of loan, loan amount and revolving balance can be used to predict the Borrower APR on a loan, the Borrower APR, Income range, Employment Status, and the Number of delinquent trades can be used to predict the loan status outcome for a borrower.

Limitations¶

In spite of the fact that our exploratory analysis gave us a lot of insightful visualizations, building predictive models would provide clearer renderings of the interaction between features and more definitive insights into the data.
